\section*{Chapter 12}

\section*{Graphons, exchangeability, and projectivity}

\subsection*{12.1 Definitions}

Consider an HVNM (Chapter 11) in which $\rho = U(0,1)$ and $p(x,y)$ is integrable, symmetric and does not depend on $n$.

\textbf{Definition 12.1.} Such a $p$ is a \emph{graphon}.

\textbf{Notes:}

\begin{itemize}
\item Graphons are actually equivalence classes of such functions: $p \simeq p'$ if there exists $\sigma$ such that $p(x,y) = p'(\sigma(x), \sigma(y))$, where $\sigma : [0,1] \to [0,1]$ is a measure-preserving map of $[0,1]$ (one can make precise the intuition that it is the $n \to \infty$ limit of permutations of integer labels $\{1, 2, ..., n\}$).

\item If neither $p$ nor $\rho$ depend on $n$, then the HVNM graphs are dense because of Eqs. (11.1) and (11.1.1) in Chapter 11.
\end{itemize}

\textbf{Definition 12.2.} Such HVNMs are \emph{$p$-random graphs} (a.k.a. $W$-random graphs since $p \equiv W$ in graph theory).

\textbf{Note:} we often call ``graphons'' the connection probability functions in other HVNMs as well!

\textbf{The simplest example:}

$p(x,y) = p$ ($p$-random graphs): $G(n,p)$.

\textbf{Key points:}

\begin{itemize}
\item Graphons are limits of dense graphs.

\item Any graph property can be ``read off'' from such a limit.

\item Graphons are the ``best thing'' that happened in network science/random graphs thus far (at least, it is most prestigiously awarded).
\end{itemize}

\subsection*{12.2 Convergence of dense graphs}

This section is about notions of graph$\to$graphon convergence: in what sense graphons are graph limits.

\subsubsection*{12.2.1 Adjacency matrix convergence}

Graphs can be mapped to graphons via chessboards.

\textbf{Definition 12.3.} The chessboard graphon $p_G$ of graph $G$:

