\subsubsection{12.2.2 Subgraph density convergence}

\textbf{Main idea:} a sequence of (random) graphs $G_n$ converge to $p(x,y)$ if the properly renormalized counts (densities) of all their subgraphs converge, because:

\begin{itemize}
\item subgraphs (motifs, ``$d$-series'') form a basis for graph decomposition/similarity analysis, so
\item the closer the densities of all subgraphs of two graphs, the more similar they are.
\end{itemize}

It is much easier to deal not with the subgraph densities, but, equivalently, with homomorphism densities.

\textbf{Definition 12.4.} A map $V(H) \to V(G)$ between vertices of two graphs $H,G$ is a homomorphism from $H$ to $G$ if edges of $H$ are mapped to edges of $G$.

\textbf{Notes:}

\begin{itemize}
\item We do not care about non-edges at all.
\item Different $H$-vertices can map to the same $G$-vertex).
\end{itemize}

\textbf{Example:}

\begin{center}
\begin{minipage}{0.8\textwidth}
Two graphs are shown side by side. On the left is graph $H$ with two vertices labeled 1 and 2, connected by two edges (a multi-edge). On the right is graph $G$ with four vertices labeled 1, 2, 3, 4 arranged in a square, with edges forming a square and additional edges. Orange arrows show a mapping from vertices of $H$ to vertices of $G$, illustrating a homomorphism.
\end{minipage}
\end{center}

\vspace{1cm}

60

\newpage

% ===== Page 3 =====
\textbf{Notes:}

\begin{itemize}
\item Let
\begin{equation}
h(H,G) = \frac{|\text{Hom}(H,G)|}{|V(G)|^{|V(H)|}}
\tag{12.1}
\end{equation}
be the probability that a random map from $V(H)$ to $V(G)$ is a homomorphism from $H$ to $G$.

\item Let
\begin{equation}
h(H,p) = \int_{[0,1]^{|V(H)|}} \prod_{(i,j)\in E(H)} p(x_i,x_j) dx_1 \ldots dx_{|V(H)|}
\tag{12.2}
\end{equation}
be the probability that graphon $p$ ``generates'' all edges of $H$.

\item If $\{G_n\}_{n=1}^{\infty}$ are graphon $p$-random graphs, then $h(H,G_n) \to h(H,p)$ for any finite simplest $H$.

\item This observation is trivial, as opposed to the other way around:
\end{itemize}

\textbf{Theorem 12.5.} \textit{Let $\{G_n\}_{n=1}^{\infty}$ be a sequence of (random) graphs. If $h(H,G_n) \to f(H) \in [0,1]$ for any finite simplest $H$, then there exists a unique graphon $p$ such that $f(H) = h(H,p)$ in Eq. (12.2).}

\textbf{Notes:}

\begin{itemize}
\item This is a very strong result, a representation theorem for $f$.

\item Converging sequences of dense graphs $\approx$ $p$-random graphs.

\item The homomorphism or subgraph frequencies can be shown to form sets of sufficient statistics in these graphs.

\item Converging sequences of dense graphs are (hypercanonical mixtures of) ERGMs in which sufficient statistics are densities of all finite subgraphs.
\end{itemize}

\subsubsection*{12.2.3 Model convergence}

\textbf{Main idea:} $G_n$ converge if so do the models $P_n$ that they define.

\textbf{Notes:}

\begin{itemize}
\item But what are those models $P_n$? And how to relate them for different $n$'s?

\item Let $G$ be a finite simplest graph, $p_G$ its chessboard graphon, $P(H|p_G)$ be the model of $p_G$-random graphs $H$ of any fixed size (finite or infinite!).

\item If $p$ is a graphon and $\{G_n\}_{n=1}^{\infty}$ is the sequence of $p$-random graphs of size $n$, then $P(H|p_{G_n}) \to P(H|p)$.

\item This observation is trivial, as opposed to the other way around:
\end{itemize}

\textbf{Theorem 12.6.} \textit{Let $\{G_n\}_{n=1}^{\infty}$ be a sequence of (random) graphs of size $n$. If $P(H|P_{G_n}) \to Q(H)$, then there exists a unique graphon $p$ such that $Q(H) = P(H|p)$.}

\textbf{Note:} this is my favorite notion of graph$\to$graphons convergence, because it avoids this scary ``for any finite simplest $H$'' requirement.

\subsubsection*{12.2.4 Other notions of convergence}

There are too many, many of which are useful.

\textbf{Mega-theorem:} pretty much all of them are equivalent.

\textbf{Notes:}

\begin{itemize}
\item In all the notions of graph$\to$graphon convergence, the graphon $p$ can be random!
\end{itemize}

\vspace{1em}
\hfill 61

\newpage

% ===== Page 4 =====
\begin{itemize}
\item This means that ``there exists a unique graphon $p$'' is actually ``there exists a unique (random) graphon $p$'', which is equivalent to saying that ``there exists a unique probability distribution $\mu$ on the space of all graphons (this space is compact!) such that $p \sim \mu$ (this is what can call an \emph{ultracanonical ensemble}).

\item In the model convergence, for example:
\[
Q(H) = \int_{\text{all graphons}} P(H|p) d\mu(p).
\]

\item A fixed (nonrandom) $p$ corresponds to an extreme point $\mu = \delta_p$.

\item \textbf{In sparse graphs:}
\begin{itemize}
\item The adjacency matrix and subgraph densities converge to zero.
\item The model convergence is unexplored.
\item There are many notions of convergence, most of which are not useful for real networks because
\item Only two are applicable to ultrasparse graphs (local weak convergence and projective limits).
\item No pair of convergence notions are known to be equivalent.
\end{itemize}
\end{itemize}

\subsection{Exchangeability}

Exchangeability is the simplest form of probabilistic symmetry. It is the symmetry w.r.t. permutations of indices of random variables (r.v.s).

\textbf{Definition 12.7.} Two r.v.s $X_1$ and $X_2$ are exchangeable if $P(X_1, X_2) = P(X_2, X_1)$.

\textbf{Examples:}

\begin{itemize}
\item $X_1, X_2 \stackrel{\text{iid}}{\sim} \text{Be}[p]$ are exchangeable.

\item $X_1 \sim \text{Be}[p_1], X_2 \sim \text{Be}[p_2]$, where $p_1 \neq p_2$, are not exchangeable.
\end{itemize}

\textbf{Definition 12.8.} An infinite sequence of r.v.s $\{X_i\}_{i=1}^\infty$ is exchangeable if $P(\{X_i\}) = P(\{X_{\sigma(i)}\})$ for any permutation $\sigma$ of indices $\{i\}$.

\textbf{Note:} above, it is either \emph{any} $\sigma$ of \emph{any} finite size $n$, or, equivalently, \emph{any} $\sigma$ of $\mathbb{N}$.

\textbf{Examples:}

\begin{enumerate}
\item $X_i \stackrel{\text{iid}}{\sim} \text{Be}[p]$.

\item (a) $p \sim \rho$, where $\rho$ is a probability distribution on $[0,1]$, and then

(b) $X_i \stackrel{\text{iid}}{\sim} \text{Be}[p]$.
\end{enumerate}

\textbf{Theorem 12.9 (De Finetti).} \emph{If $X_i$'s are Bernoullis, and $\{X_i\}_{i=1}^\infty$ is exchangeable, then it's (2) in the last example.}

\textbf{Note:} it is a strong result, a representation theorem!

\textbf{Definition 12.10.} An (infinite) array of r.v.s $\{X_{ij}\}_{i,j=1}^{n(\infty)}$ is jointly exchangeable if $P(\{X_{ij}\}) = P(\{X_{\delta(i),\delta(j)}\})$ for any permutation $\delta$ of indices $\{i\}$.

\textbf{Example:} $\{G_{ij}\}$ the adjacency matrix of $G$, a $p$-random graph with any (random) graphon.

\textbf{Definition 12.11.} A network model is finitely (infinitely) exchangeable if $P(\{G_{ij}\})$ is exchangeable for any finite (infinite) network size $n$.

\newpage

% ===== Page 5 =====
\textbf{Notes:}

\begin{itemize}
\item Permutations of indices in a network model are relabelings of nodes by meaningless integers $1, 2, \ldots$.

\item Such relabelings can either leave a graph $G$ the same labelled graph, if the relabeling is an automorphism, e.g.:

\begin{center}
\begin{minipage}{0.8\textwidth}
\textit{[Figure: Two identical triangular graphs side by side with an arrow between them. The left graph shows a triangle with vertices labeled 1 (top), 2 (left), 3 (bottom left), and 4 (bottom right). The right graph shows the same triangle structure with vertices labeled 1 (top), 2 (left), 4 (bottom left), and 3 (bottom right). This illustrates an automorphism where vertices 3 and 4 are swapped.]}
\end{minipage}
\end{center}

\item Or, if not, they change the $G$ to another labelled graph $G'$, isomorphic to $G$ ($G$ and $G'$ are the same unlabeled graph), e.g.:

\begin{center}
\begin{minipage}{0.8\textwidth}
\textit{[Figure: Two identical triangular graphs side by side with an arrow between them. The left graph shows a triangle with vertices labeled 1 (top), 2 (left), 3 (bottom left), and 4 (bottom right). The right graph shows the same triangle structure with vertices labeled 2 (top right), 1 (left), 3 (bottom left), and 4 (bottom right). This illustrates an isomorphism where vertices 1 and 2 are swapped.]}
\end{minipage}
\end{center}

\item But since these node labels are meaningless and ``do not matter'', the probability of any two isomorphic graphs in the model is the same!

\item \textbf{Exchangeability is thus:}
\begin{enumerate}
\item A simple formalization of the meaninglessness of integer node labels.
\item A required property of any network model in which integer node labels ``do not matter''.
\end{enumerate}

\item Another way to look at it:

If the network structure (an unlabeled graph) is a sufficient statistics, then the probability of a labeled graph $G$ in the model depends only on the unlabeled graph to which $G$ corresponds.
\end{itemize}

\textbf{Extremely bad news (Godel's Theorem of Network Science):}

\textbf{Theorem 12.12 (Aldous-Hoover).} \textit{If $X_{ij}$'s are Bernoullis, and $\{X_{ij}\}_{i=1}^{\infty}$ is jointly exchangeable, then it's the last example, i.e., $\{X_{ij}\}$ is the adjacency matrix of a p-random graph, where p is a (random) graphon.}

\textbf{Notes:}

\begin{itemize}
\item Historically, this theorem was proven in 1979-1981, i.e., way before the development of the graphon theory ever started ($\sim$ 2003), therefore neither Aldous nor Hoover did call $p$ a graphon.

\item Since $p$-random graphs are dense, the Aldous-Hoover theorem implies that \textit{sparse exchangeable network models are impossible}.

\item Wow, no way!!! What about $\mathcal{G}(n, p)$ with $p = k/n$ or HSCM with $p(k, k') \approx \frac{kk'}{n}$?

\item In the two ``counter-examples'' above, $p \to 0$, so \textit{the graphs are empty in the limit!}

\item \textbf{In summary,} the exchangeability dilemma is:
\begin{itemize}
\item[--] on the one hand, it is a required property of any network model in which integer node labels do not matter,
\item[--] while on the other hand, exchangeable models of sparse networks simply cannot exist.
\end{itemize}

\item Limits of sparse unlabeled graphs are entirely unexplored since it is extremely unclear how to even begin to reason about them.
\end{itemize}

\vspace{1em}
\begin{center}
63
\end{center}

