\section*{12.4 Projectivity}

\textbf{Definition 12.13.} A network model is \textit{projective} if there exists a map (called a \textit{projective map}) $\pi_{nn'}$ from graphs of size $n$ to graphs of size $n' < n$, such that:

\begin{enumerate}
    \item $\pi_{nn'}$ followed by $\pi_{n'n''}$, where $n'' < n' < n$, is $\pi_{nn''}$.
    \item $P_{n'}(G_{n'}) = \pi_{nn'}^{\sharp}[P_n(G_n)]$, where $\pi^{\sharp}$ is the push-forward of $\pi$:
    \begin{enumerate}
        \item[(a)] generate $G_n \sim P_n$,
        \item[(b)] apply $\pi_{nn'}$ to $G_n$,
        \item[(c)] the resulting $G_{n'}$ generated this way is generated with the same probability as if it was generated directly $G_{n'} \sim P_{n'}$.
    \end{enumerate}
\end{enumerate}

\textbf{Notes:}

\begin{itemize}
    \item If a model is projective, then there exists a formulation of the model as a growing network model, in which the existing network structure is not altered upon the addition of new nodes ($\pi_{nn'}^{-1}$ are node additions).
    
    \item If a model is not projective, then such a formulation does \textit{not} exist.
    
    \item Any growing network model pretending to be realistic must be \textit{local}: the addition of new nodes and links cannot have an immediate global effect affecting the whole structure of the existing network.
    
    \item Projectivity is exactly the property that captures this locality requirement.
    
    \item Therefore, \textbf{any realistic growing network model must be projective}.
    
    \item Examples of projective models:
    
    \begin{tabular}{|l|l|l|}
    \hline
    Model & Growing formulation & Projective map $\pi_{nn'}$ \\
    \hline
    Preferential attachment & Original & Remove nodes $n' + 1, n' + 2, ..., n$ \\
    \hline
    $p$-random graphs & for $n = 1, 2, ...$ & Remove any set of $n - n'$ nodes \\
    & 1) sample $X_n \sim U(0, 1)$ & \\
    & 2) for $i = 1, 2, ..., n - 1$ & \\
    & connect $n$ to $i$ with $P_{\text{ni}} = P(x_n, x_i)$ & \\
    \hline
    \end{tabular}
    
    \item Examples of non-projective models:
    \begin{enumerate}
        \item $\mathcal{G}(n, p)$ with $p = k/n$.
        \item HSCM with $P(k, k') = \frac{kk'}{kn}$.
    \end{enumerate}
    
    \item In a projective HVNM, the connection probability cannot depend on $n$.
    
    \item Aren't we missing anything here? Related to HSCM? Yes, we do!
    
    \item Recall the original $\lambda$-formulation of the HSCM with $p(\lambda, \lambda') = \frac{1}{e^{\lambda + \lambda'} + 1}$, which does not depend on $n$!
    
    \item Is the model projective then?
    
    \item Yes, but only if $\gamma = 3$, because only in this case the density and distribution of $\lambda$-points on $[-\infty, R_n]$ does not depend on $n$.
    
    \item The last point becomes obvious in the $x$-representation:
    \begin{equation}
    p_c^{CL}(x, x') = c(xx')^{-1/\alpha} n^{\frac{2}{\alpha} - 1}, \tag{12.3}
    \end{equation}
    where $c = k\left(\frac{\gamma - 2}{\gamma - 1}\right)^2$, $\alpha = \gamma - 1$, and $x \sim U(0, n)$.
\end{itemize}

\vspace{1em}
\hfill 64

\newpage

% ===== Page 7 =====
\begin{itemize}
\item If $\alpha = 2$ ($\gamma = 3$), then $\mu_x$ does not depend on $n$, while $x \sim U(0, n)$ is projective by ``space expansion'':

\begin{center}
\begin{tabular}{ccc}
\begin{tabular}{|c|}
\hline
\begin{minipage}{0.35\textwidth}
\centering
\vspace{0.3cm}
$\bullet$ \hspace{2cm} $\bullet$ \hspace{2cm} $\bullet$ \\
$x_{(1)} \leqslant x_{(n)}$ \hspace{1cm} $\leqslant$ \hspace{1cm} $x_{(n)}$ \\
$\geqslant 0$ \hspace{3cm} $\geqslant A$
\vspace{0.3cm}
\end{minipage} \\
\hline
$0$ \hspace{5.5cm} $n$
\end{tabular}
&
$\longrightarrow$
&
\begin{tabular}{|c|}
\hline
\begin{minipage}{0.45\textwidth}
\centering
\vspace{0.3cm}
$\bullet$ \hspace{1cm} $\bullet$ \hspace{1cm} $\bullet$ \hspace{1cm} $\bullet$ \hspace{1cm} $\bullet$ \hspace{0.5cm} $\longrightarrow$ \\
$x_{(1)} \leqslant x_{(n)}$ \hspace{1cm} $\leqslant$ \hspace{1cm} $x_{(n)}$ \hspace{0.5cm} $x_{n+1}$ \\
$\geqslant 0$ \hspace{3cm} $\geqslant A$ \hspace{0.5cm} $\geqslant n+1$
\vspace{0.3cm}
\end{minipage} \\
\hline
$0$ \hspace{6.5cm} $n'$ \hspace{0.5cm} $n+1$
\end{tabular}
\end{tabular}
\end{center}

\item The growing model formulation of the HSCM($\gamma = 3$)=SPA: for $n = 1, 2, ...$, sample $x_{(n)}$ as the next point in the rate-1 Poisson point process on $\mathbb{R}_+$, and connect node $n$ to existing nodes $i < n$ with $p_{n,i}^{CL} = c/\sqrt{x_{(n)}x_{(i)}}$.

\item It turns out that $k(x) \sim \sqrt{n/x}$, so $k(x_{(n)}) \sim 1$ and $p_{n,i}^{CL} \sim k_i$, so that we are dealing with soft preferential attachment (SPA).

\item The projective map $\pi_{nn'}$ removes $n - n'$ nodes with largest $x$'s (smallest $k$'s).

\item This example illustrates that the projectivity of an HVNM can be very hidden!

\item \textbf{Meta-observation:} hidden variable space expansion, coupled with $n$-independent connection probability functions, is the primary mechanism behind projectivity in sparse HVNMs.

\item We will see it is often realized in latent space models discussed in the next chapter.

\item \textbf{Meta-theorem:} any projective model has a projective limit.

\item A path towards understanding the limits of ultrasparse networks, explored at the DK-Lab.
\end{itemize}

